### 2. Working Group Documents

#### [BBRv3](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-ccwg-bbrv3-00) (discussing `draft-ietf-ccwg-bbr`)
* **Presenter:** Ian Swett
* **Key Updates:**
  * Added references to timestamp accuracy.
  * Aligned pseudocode with the normative text.
  * Neil Cardwell improved the "undo" definitions, which has shown real-world performance improvements in TCP.
  * **Precautionary Bandwidth Probing:** Designed to reduce queue pressure and packet loss. If excess loss is observed during a probe-up phase, the next probe-up cautiously stops at the long-term inflight limit, drains the queue, and checks for loss before fully resuming. This has been active in Linux TCP BBRv2/v3 since 2019 but is pending implementation in QUIC versions (Google Quiche and mvfst).
  * **ProbeRTT and MinRTT Interaction:** Extending ProbeRTT interval to 10 seconds (for better video QoE) risks expiring MinRTT right as ProbeRTT is entered, inflating the target congestion window.
* **Discussion:**
  * Alton Komaragi asked if precautionary bandwidth probing is optional. Ian Swett and Neil Cardwell confirmed it is intended to be mandatory due to its significant queue health benefits.
  * Jonathan Morton sought clarification on BBRv3 implementation details in testing.
  * Alessandro Gadini noted that Cloudflare is incrementally deploying QUIC-based BBR to production traffic.

#### [SCReAM v2](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-ccwg-scream-v2-00) (discussing `draft-ietf-ccwg-rfc8298bis-screamv2`)
* **Presenter:** Magnus Westerlund
* **Key Updates:**
  * **Queue Delay Deviation:** Changed the calculation to average the shortest and highest delay values, improving robustness against clock drift.
  * **Adaptive Reference Window:** Restricts bytes in flight during congestion but allows more overdraft when uncongested.
  * **Spurious Loss Robustness:** Window reductions upon loss now only occur if the average loss rate exceeds a threshold (default 1%) or if the queue delay is high.
* **Discussion:**
  * **Loss Thresholds & Fairness:** Christian Huitema raised concerns that treating loss on average (instead of reacting to individual drops) impacts competition between flows and might obsolete classic L4S equations which map drop rates to marking rates. Maria Apostolaki noted SCReAM enables L4S by default, and BBR also utilizes a loss threshold. 
  * **RFC 9743 Evaluation:** Magnus Westerlund asked if the evaluation against RFC 9743 should be in a separate document or an appendix. Gorry Fairhurst and Martin Duke agreed that a full RFC or massive appendix is not required; documenting the analysis in the WG's meeting materials is sufficient.
  * **Rate Policers:** Neil Cardwell recommended against implementing explicit policer detection because of added code complexity (which was removed in BBRv2 for this reason). Stuart Cheshire agreed, stating that polices should ideally signal congestion using ECN rather than forcing transport-level workarounds for packet drops.

